  "opinion": "As a working electrician in Naples with no formal education beyond primary school, I've seen firsthand how science gets reduced to wires and circuits in my shop. The gender gap isn't about girls not being smart—it's about how society tells boys to fix things while girls get told they're too delicate. My own kids, who play with both tools and dolls, show me that when we stop labeling 'science' as only for boys, everything changes. I don't have social media, so I don't see the flashy tech debates online, but in my community, women are building homes and fixing appliances just as much as we are. The real issue isn't that women can't do science—it's that we've made it feel like a man's job. We should address this by starting in schools with hands-on projects where girls can build robots and boys can draw blueprints. In Naples, where I live, we have local workshops where moms and dads learn together. I'm anxious about the future, but I know that if we let kids choose their own tools—whether it's painting or welding—then science becomes something for everyone. It's not about fixing the gap; it's about making sure everyone has a chance to fix something.",
